{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 PURGATORIO CANTO 20}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 1-3.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   The metaphoric sponge (his knowledge of this pope's experience) will not be as \softline
thoroughly saturated as the protagonist would have liked because he wishes no longer to distract \softline
Adrian, acceding instead to his clear desire to return to his penance.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 4-9.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   Virgil and Dante move along close to the wall of the mountain, away from the shades \softline
of the penitents, so thickly strewn upon this terrace but mainly near the outer edge.  That avarice \softline
has affected an enormous number of souls was also clear from }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Inferno}{\plain \fs24 \f1  VII.25.  And while Pride is \softline
often accounted the 'root sin,' another tradition gives Avarice that role.  See Trucchi (comm. to \softline
this passage) and Giacalone (comm. to vv. 7-9), the latter citing the passage in I Timothy 6:10 \softline
('Radix omnium malorum est cupiditas' [avarice is the root of all evil]) that helped form that \softline
tradition.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 10-12.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   Virgil addresses Plutus, standing over the avaricious in the fourth Circle of hell, as \softline
'maladetto lupo' (accurs{\f3 \'50}d wolf -- }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Inf}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . VII.8); the she-wolf (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 lupa}{\plain \fs24 \f1 ) who blocks Dante's upward \softline
path in }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Inferno}{\plain \fs24 \f1  I.49-54 is widely understood to represent the sin of avarice.  Here there can be no \softline
doubt: the poet apostrophizes that sin as being the most widespread among mortals.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 13-14.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   The poet's second apostrophe seeks aid from above in the hope of defeating the \softline
scourge of avarice.  Mattalia (comm. to these verses) sees these astral influences as executors of \softline
the will of God.  Kennerly M. Woody ("Dante and the Doctrine of the Great Conjunctions," \softline
}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Dante Studies}{\plain \fs24 \f1  95 [1977]), p. 122, puts a finer point upon this view, arguing that Dante is here \softline
referring to the conjunction of the planets Saturn and Jupiter every twenty years.  One such had \softline
occurred in Dante's birth year, 1265, in the constellation of Gemini (and thus in the period of \softline
Dante's birth); the next was scheduled for 1325, also in Gemini.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 15.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   Even from the very beginning of the exegetical tradition, commentators, e.g., the \softline
Anonymous Lombard (comm. to this verse) and Jacopo della Lana (comm. to vv. 13-15), believe \softline
that this opaque question refers to the}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1  veltro}{\plain \fs24 \f1  (hound) in Virgil's prophecy at }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Inferno}{\plain \fs24 \f1  I.101, thus \softline
from this vantage point lending that passage a decidedly imperial caste.  It is striking to find so \softline
much unanimity here, and so little there.  However, if there the political figure was (as some \softline
believe) Cangrande della Scala, here it would seem to be an actual emperor, Henry VII, not \softline
merely a supporter of the Ghibelline position.  Dante would have felt that Henry's advent was still \softline
in the offing, as it was until the autumn of 1310, when the emperor announced his decision to \softline
come to Italy; or else, if the passage was written in the spring of 1311, the poet, as in the view of \softline
Trucchi (comm. to vv. 13-15), was urging Henry to do what he had up to now failed to do, \softline
despite his presence in Italy: capture the city of Florence.  In his seventh Epistle, Dante's initial \softline
enthusiasm for the imperial enterprise has been reduced to overexcited and dubious hope.  See the \softline
notes to }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Purgatorio}{\plain \fs24 \f1  VI.97-102 and VII.95-96.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab These two apostrophes in the mouth of the poet (vv. 10-12 and 13-15) are suggestively \softline
coupled; the first deprecates avarice while the second calls for divine intervention in the form of \softline
an imperial presence.  We have just met a pope, who conquered the avarice that threatened to ruin \softline
him, but who, despite his best intentions, left the papacy vulnerable to the depredations of the \softline
}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 lupa}{\plain \fs24 \f1  of avarice; we are about to meet a just king (in Dante's mind not in fact a king, but the father 
of a line of kings), whose France, in his wake, will do everything it can to collaborate with the \softline
corrupt papacy in its struggle against the forces of imperial righteousness.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 19-24.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   The exemplars on this terrace are presented in an artistic medium that is \softline
parsimonious when compared to those we have been treated to on the first three terraces (see \softline
note to }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Purg}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . XVIII.99-138): here, a (temporarily) anonymous voice crying out the name and a \softline
single action of those who were noteworthy for their generosity of spirit.  As usual, the first is \softline
Mary, here remembered for giving birth to the Son of God in a stable (Luke 2:7).\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 25-30.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   'Caius Fabricius, famous Roman hero, Consul B.C. 282, 278, Censor 275.  During \softline
the invasion of Italy by Pyrrhus, King of Epirus, he was sent to the latter to negotiate an exchange \softline
of prisoners.  Pyrrhus used every effort to gain him over, but Fabricius refused all his offers.  On a \softline
later occasion he sent back to Pyrrhus the traitor who had offered to poison him, after which he \softline
succeeded in arranging terms for the evacuation of Italy by the former.  He and his contemporary \softline
Curius Dentatus are lauded by Roman writers for their frugality, and probity in refusing the bribes \softline
of the enemy' (Toynbee, "Fabbrizio" [}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Concise Dante Dictionary}{\plain \fs24 \f1 ]).  The protagonist's special \softline
pleasure in hearing of him reflects some of the poet's nearly constant enthusiasm for models of \softline
Roman republican virtue.  (For the extraordinary importance of Roman republicanism to Dante \softline
see Davis [}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Dante's Italy and Other Essays}{\plain \fs24 \f1  (Philadelphia: University of Pennsylvania Press, \softline
1984)], pp. 224-89; and see Hollander and Rossi ["Dante's Republican Treasury," }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Dante Studies}{\plain \fs24 \f1  \softline
104 (1986)], p. 75, for Fabricius's presence in four of the five collections of republican heroes \softline
offered by Dante in }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Convivio}{\plain \fs24 \f1 , }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Commedia}{\plain \fs24 \f1 , and }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Monarchia}{\plain \fs24 \f1 .)\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 31-33.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   Nicholas, whose gift-giving eventually made him the patron of Christmas, was a \softline
bishop in Asia Minor in the reign of Constantine in the fourth century.  His renown for generosity \softline
is based upon his kindness in offering dowries of gold for the three daughters of an impoverished \softline
noble friend, who had been planning to sell them into prostitution in order to maintain them and \softline
himself.  In the first two examples, poverty was itself seen as a sort of nobility, preferred both by \softline
Mary and by Fabricius to worldly wealth.  Here things are a bit different, as Nicholas allows his \softline
friend to escape from poverty by arranging for his daughters' dowries.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 34-39.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   Dante's two questions ('who were you? why do you alone cry out?') are \softline
accompanied by a promise to repay the favor of replies by procuring prayers for this penitent on \softline
earth.  These three elements will structure the rest of the canto, given over almost entirely to the \softline
words of this as yet unnamed speaker.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab The protagonist's last phrase, concerning the brevity of human life, is memorably echoed \softline
near the conclusion of this }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 cantica}{\plain \fs24 \f1  (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Purg}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . XXXIII.54: ''l viver ch'{\f3 \'50} un correre a la morte' [the life \softline
that is a race to death]).\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 40-42.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   Hugh Capet (we can infer that this is he from the next tercet, while he will offer a \softline
clear statement of his identity at verse 49) answers with the style of a man practiced in the ways of \softline
the political world.  As a gentleman, he will respond to Dante only out of the goodness of his \softline
heart because he can see that Dante lives in grace; at the same time, like the pope who spoke \softline
before him (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Purg}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . XIX.142-145), this father of a line of kings realizes there are few or none \softline
below who honor his memory.  As he converses with Dante, we can observe that half of him lives 
in this new world of grace while half of him remembers the world he left behind.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 43-45.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   As the ancestor of a line of kings of France, Hugh had a crucial role in ruling the \softline
land that now casts its desiccating shadow over the 'garden of the empire' (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Purg}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . VI.105).  We \softline
can imagine that to Dante, exiled as a result of French intervention in the affairs of Florence in \softline
collaboration with Boniface VIII in 1302, these words have a particularly bitter ring.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 46-48.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   For the series of events in Flanders that culminated in the uprising of the Flemish \softline
cities in 1302 see Singleton's commentary (to verse 46).  While the French did manage to hold on \softline
to some of the territory of Flanders, their military defeat at Courtrai in July 1302 must have \softline
seemed to Dante in some respects a punishment for what was done to Florence in the same year.  \softline
Hugh's words ring out as a prophetic hope to see his descendants justly punished, but have a \softline
particular resonance for an Italian auditor.  See Tullio Santelli ("Il canto XX del }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Purgatorio}{\plain \fs24 \f1 ,"  \softline
}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 L'Alighieri}{\plain \fs24 \f1  17 [2001]), pp. 21-23, for the political atmosphere of the Italy in which Dante was \softline
composing this very political canto, which Chiavacci Leonardi (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Purgatorio, con il commento di A. \softline
M. C. L.}{\plain \fs24 \f1  [Milan: Mondadori, 1994]), p. 579, refers to as 'the last "political" canto of the \softline
}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Purgatorio}{\plain \fs24 \f1 ' (although }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Purg}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . XXXII surely also has some claim to be so considered).\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 49.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   The speaker at last fully identifies himself as Hugh Capet, who was in fact king of \softline
France (987-996), even if Dante did not know him as such.  'The statements put by Dante into the \softline
mouth of Hugh Capet as to the origin of the Capetian dynasty are in several respects at variance \softline
with the historical facts, and can only be explained on the supposition that Dante has confused \softline
Hugh Capet with his father, Hugh the Great,...  The facts are as follows: Hugh the Great died in \softline
956; Louis V, the last of the Carlovingians, died in 987, in which year Hugh Capet became king; \softline
on his death in 996, he was succeeded by his son Robert, who had previously been crowned in \softline
988 [to assure a Capetian continuity upon Hugh's eventual death].  Dante makes Hugh Capet say: \softline
firstly, that he was the son of a butcher of Paris (verse 52), whereas common tradition assigned \softline
this origin not to Hugh Capet, but to his father, Hugh the Great; second, that when the \softline
Carlovingians came to an end he was so powerful that he was able to make his son king (vv. 53-60), whereas on the failure of the Carlovingian line Hugh Capet himself became king (987); and \softline
third, that with his son the Capetian line began (vv. 59-60), whereas in fact it began with himself' \softline
(Toynbee, "Ciapetta, Ugo" [}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Concise Dante Dictionary}{\plain \fs24 \f1 ]).  Hugh's control of the power over \softline
kingship is the }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 alpha}{\plain \fs24 \f1  of which the rule of Philip the Fair, the French king as Dante was writing, is \softline
the }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 omega}{\plain \fs24 \f1 .  For a treatment of the historical details see Rajna ("'Ugo Ciappetta' nella }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Divina \softline
Commedia}{\plain \fs24 \f1  [}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Purgatorio}{\plain \fs24 \f1 , canto XX]," }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Studi Danteschi}{\plain \fs24 \f1  37 [1960 (1924)], pp. 5-20).  On the \softline
particulars of Hugh's speech see also Riccardo Scrivano ("L'orazione politica di Ugo Capeto," \softline
}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 L'Alighieri}{\plain \fs24 \f1  2 [1971], pp. 13-34).\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 50-51. }{\plain \fs24 \f1  Bosco/Reggio (comm. to verse 50) offer a list of the ten kings who followed Hugh \softline
to the throne between 996 and 1314.  Four of these indeed bore the name 'Philip' and four, 'Louis,' \softline
but it is the last in each of these groups who may be of greatest interest.  Louis IX (1226-1270) is \softline
one of the major figures of the Middle Ages, a great crusader, king, and saint.  Of him Dante is -- \softline
perhaps not surprisingly, given his hatred of France -- resolutely silent; of Philip IV (the Fair -- \softline
1285-1314), he is loquacity itself, vituperating him several times in this canto, but also in a \softline
number of other passages (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Inf}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . XIX.85-87; }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Purg}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . VII.109-110; XXXII.155-156; }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Par}{\plain \fs24 \f1 .XIX.118-120).\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 52.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   For Dante's repetition of this common error concerning Hugh's paternity see \softline
Toynbee's remarks in the note to verse 49.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 53-54.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   Again Dante is misled, perhaps confusing events in the eighth century surrounding \softline
the last days of the Merovingian line, when Pippin the Short }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 did}{\plain \fs24 \f1  put away his last possible \softline
political rival in a monastery.  What Hugh had done was to have the last of the Carolingians, the \softline
Duke of Lorraine, imprisoned in 991.  He remained in prison until his death a year later.  See \softline
Bosco/Reggio's comment on verse 54.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 55-60.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   Hugh's account of himself as kingmaker is, once again, not in accord with history \softline
(see Toynbee, above in the note to verse 49): it was immediately after he himself was made king \softline
that he had his son, Robert, anointed as his successor.  Thus his account of himself as father of the \softline
first of the line is an unwitting act of modesty, since he himself was the first in it.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 61-66.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   Hugh offers a brief and allusive recapitulation of four centuries of French \softline
expansionism, beginning with the continuing efforts to annex Provence, which avoided this fate \softline
until 1246, when a marriage between the brother of Louis IX, Charles of Anjou, was arranged \softline
with Beatrice, daughter of Raymond Berenger IV of Provence.  And then, to make amends for \softline
this perfidy (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 per ammenda}{\plain \fs24 \f1  will be repeated, with increasing sarcasm, to create a triple identical \softline
rhyme, twice in the following tercet), France consolidated its territories by annexing three other \softline
territories that had been independent.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 67-81.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   And now the really dreadful deeds begin: a descent into the Italian peninsula where \softline
a series of members of the French royal house named Charles are given employment by being sent \softline
into Italy: Charles of Anjou, who is blamed for killing Conradin (the last hope of Italian \softline
Ghibellinism) at Tagliacozzo in 1268 (see }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Inf}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . XXVIII.17-18) and for poisoning Thomas Aquinas \softline
in 1274 (a rumor that appears to have been made out of whole cloth as part of Italian anti-French \softline
propaganda, but which Dante seems only too willing to propagate).  Then Charles de Valois will \softline
take (we are once again in the realm of }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 post-factum}{\plain \fs24 \f1  prophecy) Florence in 1301 on behalf of an \softline
alliance among the French, the papacy of Boniface, and the Black Guelphs of Corso Donati; it is \softline
not difficult to imagine Dante's outrage at the intervention of this second Charles.  Finally, the \softline
third of these wretched Frenchmen, Charles II, son of Charles of Anjou and king of Naples, is \softline
brought on stage to suffer Dante's taunts, delivered by this French version of Dante's ancestor \softline
Cacciaguida (see }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Par}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . XV-XVII), a benevolent ancestor of (in this case) an undeserving \softline
descendant.  This Charles is portrayed as, after having lost a calamitous naval battle during the \softline
Sicilian Vespers in 1284 and, as a result, being held prisoner on his own ship, selling his daughter \softline
(there having been no intervention from St. Nicholas on his behalf, we may assume) into \softline
matrimony with Azzo VIII of Este in 1305.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 82-84.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   Hugh's first apostrophe of Avarice parallels Dante's at vv. 10-12.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 85-90.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   And now the worst of all the French arrives for his excoriation, King Philip IV \softline
(see note to }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Purg}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . VII.103-111 and to vv. 50-51, above).  This king, who had been 
excommunicated by Boniface as a result of their dispute over the French king's desire to tax the \softline
clergy, had his revenge when, in September 1303, the king's representative, William of Nogaret, \softline
accompanied by an Italian ally, Sciarra Colonna, a member of the family that Boniface, aided by \softline
the advice of Guido da Montefeltro, had harmed (see }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Inf}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . XXVII.102), arrived in Anagni with a \softline
force of soldiers and, after physically assaulting the elderly pope, imprisoned him in his own \softline
palace, which they sacked.  Boniface was eventually freed in a popular uprising against these \softline
intruders and made his way to Rome.  But the insult to his person, both physical and spiritual, was \softline
apparently so great that he died on 12 October 1303.  For a description in English of the outrage \softline
done to Boniface see Carroll's commentary (comm. to vv. 85-96).\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab Dante was no admirer of Boniface.  The French attack upon the person of the pope, \softline
however, was an attack upon the holy office itself, and thus upon the Mystical Body of Christ, the \softline
Church.  And thus Boniface is compared to Christ betrayed by Pontius Pilate and crucified, while \softline
the agents of Philip become the two thieves present at that event, but now represented as part of \softline
the torture administered to their victim.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab For the possible dependence of Dante's verses here on a poetic prayer to the Virgin \softline
composed by Boniface see Moore (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Studies in Dante}{\plain \fs24 \f1 , Second Series: }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Miscellaneous Essays}{\plain \fs24 \f1  \softline
[Oxford: Clarendon, 1968 (1899)], pp. 396-97); for the text of this poem see Robert Artinian \softline
("Dante's Parody of Boniface VIII," }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Dante Studies}{\plain \fs24 \f1  85 [1967], pp. 71-74).\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 91-93.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   The 'new Pilate' now directs his rage against the Templars.  (For a more balanced \softline
view than Dante's of Philip's motives see Scott [}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Dante's Political Purgatory}{\plain \fs24 \f1  (Philadelphia: \softline
University of Pennsylvania Press, 1996)], pp. 174-77.)  'The Knights Templars were one of the \softline
three great military orders founded in Cent. xii for the defence of the Latin Kingdom of Jerusalem.  \softline
After having existed as a powerful and wealthy order for nearly two centuries they were in 1307 \softline
accused by Philip the Fair of heresy, sacrilege, and other hideous offences, in consequence of \softline
which he ordered their arrest, and by means of diabolical tortures wrung from them confessions \softline
(for the most part undoubtedly false) of their alleged enormities.  Five years later, at Philip's \softline
instigation, they were condemned by Clement V, and the order was suppressed by decree of the \softline
Council of Vienne (May, 1312); in the following year the Grand Master, Du Molay, was burned \softline
alive at Paris in the presence of the king.  The French king's motive in aiming at the destruction of \softline
the Templars was, it can hardly be doubted, a desire to get possession of the immense wealth of \softline
the order, as is implied by Dante, and stated in so many words by Villani (viii.92)' (Toynbee, \softline
"Templari" [}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Concise Dante Dictionary}{\plain \fs24 \f1 ]).  When did Dante write this passage?  Clearly sometime \softline
after 1307; and, perhaps nearly as clearly, before 1312.  It is notable that none of the details of the \softline
denouement of this ugly scheme reached Dante's page: }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 sanza decreto}{\plain \fs24 \f1  (unsanctioned) the king sets \softline
out without the papal support necessary to justify such an action (it would come from that other \softline
detested Frenchman, Pope Clement V, only in 1312).  \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 94-96.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   Hugh's second apostrophe parallels Dante's (vv. 13-15) in hoping for divine \softline
vengeance to descend from above and smite the guilty, in this case most particularly Philip the \softline
Fair.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab There are questions as to whether the poet meant the reader to think of the 'vengeance' as \softline
reflecting his defeats in Flanders in 1302 (see Singleton [comm. to verse 96]), or Philip's death \softline
while hunting, when his horse was overturned by a charging boar, in 1314 (the opinion of John of \softline
Serravalle [comm. to these verses]), or neither of these events.  As Trucchi (comm. to these 
verses) points out, Dante clearly refers with joy to Philip's death in November 1314 at }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Paradiso}{\plain \fs24 \f1  \softline
XIX.118-120.  The notion that God's vengeance for the events at Anagni in 1303 occurred in \softline
Flanders in 1302 hardly seems acceptable.  Further, as Bosco/Reggio (comm. to these verses) \softline
argue, since Dante does refer to Philip's death in the next }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 cantica}{\plain \fs24 \f1 , it only makes sense to believe \softline
that he did not yet know of it when he wrote this passage, for it would have been much too \softline
tempting a piece of information not to include.  In any case, the result is as Dante probably would \softline
have wanted anyway; here he predicts only that such outrageous behavior will receive God's \softline
eventual vengeance -- it is but a matter of time.  This seems the best understanding.  The gleeful \softline
passage in }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Paradiso}{\plain \fs24 \f1  banks the promissory note that Dante writes us here.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab Scartazzini (comm. to verse 95) was perhaps the first to cite, as a source for the oblique \softline
phrasing of this tercet, which causes some readers difficulty, Psalm 57:11 (58:10): 'Laetabitur \softline
