}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 127-129.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   The sudden shift in focus to Dante's fearful condition in response to this \softline
earthquake opens an entirely new chapter in the narrative, a unique one.  As Philip B. Miller \softline
observed in conversation many years ago, Statius's completion of penance is the only genuine \softline
event that occurs involving a damned or a saved soul in the entire }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Commedia}{\plain \fs24 \f1 .  (Discussion of \softline
Statius awaits the next canto.)  All else in the poem that passes for narrative action pertains to \softline
demons or angels interacting with Dante, Virgil, or the souls whom they help to punish to serve, \softline
to Dante's own difficulties or successes in moving on, or else represents some form of ritual \softline
performance by the souls in the afterworld for the benefit of onlooking Dante.  Dante, still a \softline
stranger on this magic mountain, responds by feeling like a man in fear of death.  We shortly learn \softline
that he is witness to a moment of completion, of resurrection.  It takes a while for this to become \softline
clear.\par
